         <div type="translation">
            <p>
               <choice corresp="#a1">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... wisdom looking at the Brahmaloka (?) ... Of whomever he drives away such passion ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a2">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>81</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in the <hi>·m·nnaṃ</hi> [tune] || The pleasure of thinking with eyes, without shaking, is good for him ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a3">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>249</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... a <hi>kuṣt</hi> animal [predator] is placed [at] his feet. They who are smiling a little, full of love (for the beings) ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a4">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the teeth right now exceedingly evoke panic (?). 1. <hi>yreki</hi> with love ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a5">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>47</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... now the deep holes in the skull evoke fear. Adorned [pl.] ...</seg></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... jetzt rufen die tiefen Löcher in dem [Toten]schädel Furcht hervor.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">... now, the deep holes in this skull arouse fear.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>330</citedRange></bibl></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a6">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... now they evoke unpleasantness of thinking. (2.) Touched [pl.] by love ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b1">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they are now devoured by the <hi>lepś</hi> [animals] with [their] fangs. Confused [pl.] by love ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b2">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he [is] without refuge [and] protection. Where is he dragged by the <hi>kuṣt</hi> animals [predator]s? 3. [Their] venes ...</seg></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (ist?) er ohne Schutz [und] Zuflucht. Wohin wohl wird er von den kuṣt-Raubtieren gezerrt?</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">... (is?) without shelter [and] protection. Whereto is he being dragged by the kuṣt-beasts?</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>255</citedRange></bibl></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b3">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... with consciousness. The fools are confused by passion [and] go away from the path ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b4">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the knowing ones do not begin ... Female chat [and] gesticulation ... </seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b5">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>112</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>125</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... with consideration the compassionate being in the large cemetery forest ... large ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b6">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>174, 175</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... wishing to ... || Thereupon, on a high <hi>cuṣiṃ</hi> pole placed upright ...</seg></seg>
               </choice>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p>
               <note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment"><hi>äñcesnine</hi>: gen.pl.m. of <hi>äntsanne</hi> 'whoever' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>60b</citedRange></bibl>; Siegling personal copy of <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1921"/></bibl>).</note>
               <note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>/// ·m·nnaṃ</hi>: the name of a tune with the metre 4 x 18 (7+7+4). It contains 4 strophes and continues until the beginning of line b5. The strophe does not end after the strophe number "1" in a4, because (pace <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1921"/><citedRange>32</citedRange></bibl>) no double daṇḍa "||" follows.</note>
               <note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">16 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (3 of pāda 1a and 13 of pāda 1b).</note>
               <note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">15 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (8 of pāda 1c and 7 of pāda 1d).</note>
               <note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">20 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (14 of pāda 2a and 6 of pāda 2b).</note>
               <note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment"><hi>tsārot</hi>: the meaning of this word is unknown. It may be an adverb in view of the apparent suffix <hi>-ot</hi> (cf. <hi>wtākot</hi> 'for the second time' next to <hi>wtā</hi>, <hi>wtāk</hi>).</note>
               <note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">25 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (14 of pāda 2c and 9 of pāda 2d). Instead of <hi>pälskes :</hi> one would have expected <hi>pälskes : 2</hi>.</note>
               <note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">24 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (15 of pāda 3a and 9 of pāda 3b).</note>
               <note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">24 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (14 of pāda 3c and 10 of pāda 3d).</note>
               <note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">14 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (all of pāda 4a).</note>
               <note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">16 syllables missing at the beginning of the line (7 of pāda 4b and 9 of pāda 4c).</note>
               <note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">The last 10 syllables of the last pāda (4d) and the beginning of the prose passage (probably the number 4, a double daṇḍa and approximately 8 more syllables) are missing at the beginning of the line.</note>
               <note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment"><hi>käryatsum</hi>: probably an infinitive was preceding, i.e. <hi>... (t)s(i) käryatsum</hi>.</note>
               <note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment"><hi>cuṣiṃṣi</hi>: the word division is uncertain (<bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>174</citedRange></bibl> rather reads <hi>cu ṣiṃṣi</hi> and translates "Dann dich aufrecht aufgestellt, wie <hi>an einem</hi> hohen *<hi>ṣiṃ-Pfosten</hi> ..."). For the possible word <hi>cuṣiṃ</hi>, here as a <hi>ṣi</hi>-adjective, cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1514"/> a3. It may be a borrowing from Skt. <hi>cūṣiṇī</hi>, name "of a female attendant of Durgā" (<bibl><title corresp="ref:monierwilliams1899"/><citedRange>401b</citedRange></bibl>).</note>
            </p>
